Iraqi exiles in Australia and New Zealand were the first to vote in the historic national elections, amidst intensified attacks by insurgents.
President George W. Bush urged Iraqis to seize the "historic opportunity" to vote despite threats.
The Al-Qaeda Group executed a candidate, and violence escalated with car bombings and attacks on polling stations.
US and British troops planned withdrawal as casualties rose.
Despite security measures, attacks continued, targeting voting stations and civilians.
The election faced boycott threats from Sunni groups, reflecting deep divisions among Iraq's major factions.
The violence underscored the challenges of achieving stability through democratic processes.
